Kedgeree – A Very Scottish Curry

   image

   Curry powder, eggs, rice…. I haven’t made this one in a while but it’s
   certainly one Scottish recipe you should definitely try.

   Now you might ask the question, “Curry powder in a traditional Scottish
   recipe?” but the answer is Yes, apparently it was a Scottish regiment
   serving in India that married local curry with smoked fish. “Finnan
   haddies” (smoked haddock named for the fishing village of Finnan or
   Findon in Scotland) or “Arbroath smokies” would be best but most smoked
   fish is fine.

   I generally use smoked haddock from the local supermarket but I do try
   to get the ‘undyed’ variety if I can, it’s less garish in colour and
   has a truer smoked flavour.

   This dish is often served as a breakfast alternative, but is equally
   suited as a light lunch or supper dish.

   Ingredients: (serves 4)
     * 2 fillets of smoked haddock, bones and skin removed
     * 4 hard boiled eggs, shelled and chopped roughly
     * 350g/ 3?4lb long grain basmati rice (or brown rice)
     * 300ml/ 10fl oz of milk to poach the fish
     * 50g/ 2oz of butter
     * 750ml/ 11?4 pints of chicken stock
     * One small onion, peeled and finely chopped
     * One bay leaf
     * One teaspoon curry powder (or to your own taste!)
     * Half teaspoon grated nutmeg
     * Ground pepper (to taste)

   Method:
     * Pre-heat the oven to 180C/350F/Gas Mark 4.
     * Cook the onion gently in the butter and add the rice, stirring to
       coat the rice in butter.
     * Add the stock and bring to the boil.
     * Add the bay leaf, cover and cook in the oven for about 20 minutes
       or until the rice has absorbed the stock. Remove the bay leaf at
       the end of cooking.
     * Poach the fish in hot milk for five minutes and drain just before
       the rice is ready.
     * Flake the fish.
     * When the rice is ready, stir in the flaked fish, chopped eggs,
       curry powder, nutmeg and pepper, using a fork to stir the flaked
       fish (to prevent the rice from breaking up).
     * Serve with buttered toast and a mug of hot tea.

   Thanks to Derek McGuff for this delicious item
     *
